"""
MKT Context -- Luke 4-5
Output: data/commentary/mkt-context/luke.json

Historical, social, and intertextual context for each verse.
Ch4: Wilderness temptation (Deut 6-8 intertexts), Nazareth inaugural sermon
  (Isa 61 / Jubilee context, Elijah-Elisha precedents), Capernaum exorcism
  and healings.
Ch5: Miraculous catch and first disciples (Gennesaret fishing economy),
  leper cleansing (Levitical purity system), paralytic controversy (Son of Man
  authority), Levi's call (tax collection customs), fasting-and-wineskin debate.
"""
import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists(): return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: merge new_data into existing without overwriting any present entry
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing: existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]: existing[ch][v] = html

NEW = {
'4': {
'1': '<p>The temptation narrative occurs immediately after Jesus\' baptism and the Spirit\'s descent (3:21-22). Luke\'s phrasing -- "full of the Holy Spirit" and "led by the Spirit into the wilderness" -- sets up the test as a Spirit-empowered confrontation. The wilderness (eremos) recalls Israel\'s forty years of wilderness testing (Deut 8:2: "to humble and test you"); Jesus\' forty days recapitulates and reverses Israel\'s failures. Jewish apocalyptic tradition associated the wilderness with both divine encounter (Elijah: 1 Kgs 19:8; Moses: Exod 24:18; 34:28) and demonic presence (Isa 34:14; Bar 4:35; 1 Enoch 10).</p>',
'2': '<p>Fasting for forty days connects Jesus to Moses (Exod 34:28: "He was there with the Lord forty days and forty nights; he neither ate bread nor drank water") and Elijah (1 Kgs 19:8). Prolonged fasting was practiced in Second Temple Judaism as a means of intensifying prayer and visionary experience (Dan 10:3; 4 Ezra 5:19-20). "The devil" (diabolos) is the LXX rendering of the Hebrew Satan (ha-satan = the accuser), a figure prominent in Job 1-2, Zech 3:1-2, and 1 Chr 21:1. Luke uses diabolos rather than Satanas here, emphasizing the role of adversarial accuser familiar to Hellenistic readers.</p>',
'3': '<p>The first temptation exploits the vulnerability of genuine hunger. The command "tell this stone to become bread" echoes the wilderness provision crisis of Exod 16 (manna). Jesus\' sonship is challenged: "If you are the Son of God" -- the same taunt used at the crucifixion (23:35-39). In Deut 8:3 (which Jesus will cite), Moses frames the manna not as provision secured by human ingenuity but as divine teaching that "man does not live by bread alone." The temptation is to resolve physical need through autonomous power rather than trust.</p>',
'4': '<p>Jesus cites Deut 8:3 from the LXX: "Man shall not live on bread alone." The Deuteronomy context (chs 6-8) is the foundational OT background for all three temptation responses: Deut 6:13 (worship God alone), Deut 6:16 (do not test), and Deut 8:3 (do not live by bread alone). Jesus thus positions himself as the faithful son who succeeds where Israel (also called God\'s son, Exod 4:22) failed in the wilderness. The omission of "but by every word of God" present in Matt 4:4 and Deut 8:3 in some Lukan manuscripts is a textual variant; most editions retain it.</p>',
'5': '<p>The second temptation shifts to a panoramic vision of all the kingdoms of the world. "In an instant" (en stigme chronou) highlights the supernatural character of the revelation. The motif of a high mountain from which all kingdoms are visible appears in Jewish apocalyptic: Deut 34:1-3 (Moses sees the whole land from Nebo), 4 Ezra 11-12 (eagle vision), and 1 Enoch 18. The idea that the kingdoms of this world are under the devil\'s authority reflects a strand of Jewish apocalyptic thought that saw the present age as under evil-angelic dominion (cf. Dan 10:13, 20; Eph 6:12; John 12:31).</p>',
'6': '<p>Satan\'s claim to have been "given" authority over the kingdoms and to give it to whomever he wishes reflects the dualistic cosmology common in Second Temple apocalyptic literature (1 Enoch 6-11; Jub. 48:9-19; Testament of Moses 10; Qumran\'s dualistic texts like 1QS 3-4). The language of being "handed over" (paradedotai) echoes the Danielic vision of successive kingdoms given by God to earthly rulers. The offer targets the messianic expectation of universal kingship -- the temptation is to grasp the kingdoms through accommodation to evil rather than through the cross.</p>',
'7': '<p>The condition of the temptation -- "if you worship before me" -- is the demand for proskynesis (prostration before a king or deity), the honor gesture of the Hellenistic world. In the Augustan context of the Roman Empire, emperor worship was beginning to require proskynesis. The temptation reflects the real political-religious pressure of the first century: to achieve dominance by adopting the world\'s methods of power. Jesus\' refusal positions him in opposition to every form of political idolatry.</p>',
'8': '<p>Jesus cites Deut 6:13: "Worship the Lord your God and serve him only." The Shema context (Deut 6:4-9, the daily Jewish prayer) is deliberately invoked -- this is not merely a proof text but the foundational confession of Jewish monotheism. "Serve him only" (aut&#333; mon&#333; latreuseis) uses latreuō, the Greek word for cultic service/worship, the same word used in the LXX for Israel\'s liturgical worship of God. The application to Satan\'s offer: his service is not latreia but the abandonment of the one true God.</p>',
'9': '<p>The temple pinnacle (pterygion tou hierou) was probably the southeast corner of the temple mount, where the Royal Stoa overhangs the Kidron Valley -- a drop of some 450 feet according to Josephus (Ant. 15.411-12). This was the highest visible point of the entire temple complex. In rabbinic tradition, a legend circulated that the Messiah would appear on the roof of the temple (j. Berakhot 2:4). The temptation is to perform a spectacular messianic sign that would force God\'s protective response -- to "test" God by compelling a miracle.</p>',
'10': '<p>Satan cites Ps 91:11-12 (the psalm of divine protection) accurately, demonstrating that Scripture can be weaponized for false purposes. Psalm 91 was widely used in Second Temple Judaism as protection against demonic attack (4QPsAp = 11Q11, an Aramaic Psalms scroll uses this psalm in an exorcism formula). The irony: a psalm designed to protect the faithful from spiritual harm is used by the adversary to provoke presumption.</p>',
'11': '<p>The angels who "will lift you up so that you will not strike your foot against a stone" (Ps 91:12) evokes the tradition of guardian angels. Jewish angelology in the Second Temple period expanded significantly: Gabriel and Michael as archangels (Dan 8:16; 10:13; 1 Enoch 9), guardian angels for individuals (Tob 5:4-16; Matt 18:10), and angelic protection of the righteous (Ps 34:7; Dan 6:22). The temptation to spectacular display exploits the genuine promise of protection to serve self-promotion.</p>',
'12': '<p>Jesus cites Deut 6:16: "Do not put the Lord your God to the test." The Deuteronomy context is the incident at Massah (Exod 17:1-7), where Israel tested God by demanding water: "Is the Lord among us or not?" To test (ekpeirazō) God is to demand that he prove himself on human terms -- a fundamental inversion of faith. "Tempting the Lord" by the spectacular jump would be forcing God to act on a human schedule to prove his protective presence.</p>',
'13': '<p>"Until an opportune time" (achri kairou) is a programmatic marker in Luke. The devil\'s departure is temporary; Luke explicitly connects Satan\'s return to the passion: 22:3 ("Satan entered Judas"), 22:31 ("Satan has asked to sift all of you as wheat"), 22:53 ("this is your hour -- when darkness reigns"). The "opportune time" anticipates the full assault of the passion, framing Luke\'s entire Gospel as a single extended conflict between the Spirit-empowered Jesus and the adversary who retreats only to return at the cross.</p>',
'14': '<p>The return to Galilee "in the power of the Spirit" (en t&#275; dynamei tou pneumatos) transitions from the private temptation ordeal to the public ministry. Galilee in the first century was a prosperous agricultural and fishing region under Herod Antipas\'s tetrarchy, with a mixed population of Jews and Gentiles on its margins. Its distance from Jerusalem and its reputation as provincial (John 7:52: "no prophet comes from Galilee") makes it an unlikely starting point for messianic activity. The "reports" (ph&#275;m&#275;) spreading through the region anticipates the fame-and-withdrawal pattern of the Galilean ministry.</p>',
'15': '<p>Synagogue teaching was the primary vehicle for the spread of Jesus\' ministry in Galilee. First-century synagogues served as community centers for study, prayer, legal assembly, and social welfare -- not merely houses of worship. The synagogue structure involved Torah reading (in Hebrew with Aramaic targum interpretation), a Prophets reading (haftarah), a sermon, and prayer. Any qualified adult male could be invited to read and expound. Jesus\' teaching role "in their synagogues" (en tais synagogais aut&#333;n) is Luke\'s summary of the Galilee phase before the Nazareth crisis.</p>',
'16': '<p>Nazareth was a small village (perhaps 200-400 inhabitants) in Lower Galilee. The "synagogue of Nazareth" would have been a modest village assembly hall. Luke emphasizes Jesus\' habitual practice: "as was his custom" (kata to eiothos = according to his usual practice). The scroll of Isaiah was one of the most widely copied prophetic texts found at Qumran (22 copies of Isaiah among the Dead Sea Scrolls, more than any other book). The scrolls were housed in the synagogue and managed by the hazzan (attendant), who handed them to the reader.</p>',
'17': '<p>The Isaiah scroll handed to Jesus was a physical parchment scroll (megill&#257;h). The reader unrolled (anoixas) the scroll to find the desired passage -- without chapter divisions or pagination, requiring familiarity with the text. Luke specifies that Jesus "found the place" where the Isa 61 passage was written, suggesting deliberate selection rather than the assigned lectionary reading. The absence of a fixed haftarah lectionary in the first century (the triennial cycle developed later) means the reader had some freedom in Prophets selection.</p>',
'18': '<p>Isaiah 61:1-2 is the Jubilee charter of Israel\'s liberation. The Jubilee (Lev 25:8-55) mandated every fiftieth year: release of debts, freeing of slaves, return of alienated land. By the first century, the Jubilee had not been observed for centuries and had taken on eschatological significance -- the great Jubilee that God would inaugurate in the messianic age. The Qumran community used Isa 61 messianically (11QMelchizedek applies it to the eschatological figure Melchizedek). "Good news to the poor" (euangelisasthai pt&#333;chois) uses the same vocabulary as the Isaiah 40 herald whose voice cries in the wilderness (3:4).</p>',
'19': '<p>"The year of the Lord\'s favor" (eniauton Kyriou dekton) is the Jubilee year of Lev 25:10 ("proclaim liberty throughout the land to all its inhabitants"). Isaiah 61:2 adds "the day of vengeance of our God" -- significantly, Jesus stops reading mid-sentence at "year of the Lord\'s favor" and does not read "the day of vengeance." This deliberate omission has been noted by interpreters since the early church: Jesus\' mission is the Jubilee of grace; the judgment element is deferred. The selection and truncation of the text is itself an interpretive act.</p>',
'20': '<p>The hazzan (synagogue attendant) was responsible for the care of the sacred scrolls, the building maintenance, and the logistics of the reading. Rolling the scroll back up (ptuxas) and returning it to the attendant followed standard synagogue protocol. Jesus then "sat down" -- the teacher\'s posture in Judaism (the seated teacher of authority, as in Matt 5:1; 23:2: "the scribes and Pharisees sit in Moses\' seat"). The congregation\'s gaze (atenizontes) signals the heightened expectation before the exposition begins.</p>',
'21': '<p>"Today this scripture is fulfilled in your hearing" -- the programmatic statement of Lukan inaugurated eschatology. S&#275;meron (today) is one of Luke\'s characteristic terms: 2:11 (born today), 4:21 (fulfilled today), 19:5 (today I must stay), 19:9 (today salvation has come), 23:43 (today you will be with me in paradise). The "today" of the kingdom\'s arrival is not a future expectation but a present reality in the person of Jesus. "In your hearing" (en tois ōsin hym&#333;n) makes the congregation not merely audience but witnesses of fulfillment.</p>',
'22': '<p>The initial response combines admiration (ethaumazon = they marveled) with the words of grace (tois logois t&#275;s charitos). The question "Isn\'t this Joseph\'s son?" is the identity challenge. In honor-shame culture, a craftsman\'s son from a village had no standing to make prophetic claims of fulfillment -- his social location was known and fixed. The question is not necessarily hostile; it reflects bewilderment at the gap between the claim and the known social status. The shift from wonder to fury (v.28) when Jesus invokes the Gentile precedents is the narrative\'s sharp turn.</p>',
'23': '<p>"Physician, heal yourself" was a known proverb in antiquity. The Talmud preserves a version (b. Bava Kamma 85a). Seneca uses the Greek equivalent (Ep. 27.1). The proverb carries the sense: demonstrate by what you do for yourself what you claim to do for others. Jesus anticipates the challenge: you did great things in Capernaum -- do the same here. The pairing reveals that news of his Capernaum ministry has already reached Nazareth -- the fame of v.14 has preceded him.</p>',
'24': '<p>"No prophet is accepted in his hometown" (en t&#275; patridi autou) is a proverbial form attested also in the Gospel of Thomas (logion 31) and echoed in John 4:44. The proverb reflects a sociological reality of honor-shame cultures: familiarity breeds skepticism; the known social status makes extraordinary claims incredible. Luke\'s version uses "accepted" (dektos) -- the same word used in v.19 for the "year of the Lord\'s favor" (eniauton Kyriou dekton). The rejected prophet does not receive the receptivity (dektos) that characterizes God\'s Jubilee.</p>',
'25': '<p>The Elijah reference (1 Kgs 17-18) is the first of two Gentile-mission precedents Jesus invokes. Elijah\'s ministry under Ahab included the three-and-a-half-year drought (1 Kgs 18:1 says three years; Luke\'s three and a half years aligns with an apocalyptic tradition used in Dan 7:25; 12:7; Rev 11:2; 12:14). "Many widows in Israel" -- the contrast is between the abundance of need within Israel and the divine choice to send Elijah to the Phoenician widow of Zarephath (Sidon). Zarephath (modern Sarafand, Lebanon) was pagan territory -- a pointed example of God\'s provision bypassing Israel.</p>',
'26': '<p>The widow of Zarephath (1 Kgs 17:8-24) was a Phoenician Gentile to whom Elijah was sent during the famine. The Zarephath episode includes the miraculous provision of flour and oil, and the raising of her son from death. By citing this precedent, Jesus implicitly analogizes his own ministry: like Elijah, his most receptive audience may be outside Israel\'s ethnic boundaries. The Gentile-mission implication is the precipitating cause of the Nazareth crowd\'s fury (v.28) -- it is not merely hometown pride but the theological scandal of Gentile inclusion that provokes the violent response.</p>',
'27': '<p>Naaman the Syrian (2 Kgs 5:1-14) was a military commander of Aram (Syria) -- not only a Gentile but an enemy of Israel. His leprosy (skin condition) was healed by Elisha\'s instruction to wash seven times in the Jordan, despite his preference for "better" Syrian rivers. The point Jesus makes: "there were many lepers in Israel in the time of Elisha, and not one of them was cleansed -- only Naaman the Syrian." The divine freedom to heal a foreign enemy rather than Israelite sufferers is the theological principle that makes the Nazareth crowd furious. This anticipates the Gentile centurion (7:9), the Samaritan leper (17:16), and the Gentile mission of Acts.</p>',
'28': '<p>"All the people in the synagogue were furious" (eplēsth&#275;san ... thumou) -- the transition from wonder to violent fury is rapid. Thymos (fury/rage) is the sudden passion that accompanies honor violation. The crowd has understood what Jesus implies: that the Jubilee he announces will not prioritize Israel, that Gentile outsiders may receive what Nazareth refuses. This is read as a prophetic insult and a rejection of Jewish privilege. The violence that follows (vv.29-30) anticipates the rejection and death that the Gentile-inclusive mission will bring.</p>',
'29': '<p>The brow of the hill on which Nazareth was built -- the topography of ancient Nazareth included a ridge running above the settlement. Tradition identifies the location with the Precipice of Nazareth (modern Jebel Qafza, about 4 km south of the old city), though this identification is disputed; others locate the "brow" at the ridge directly above the ancient village. The attempted mob execution echoes the stoning procedure for blasphemers (Lev 24:14-16; Acts 7:57-58 for Stephen\'s stoning) with the preliminary casting out of the city before the execution.</p>',
'30': '<p>"He walked right through the crowd and went on his way" -- Jesus\' unharmed passage through the mob has been interpreted as miraculous divine protection (cf. John 8:59; 10:39), as a natural result of the crowd\'s hesitation, or as Luke\'s theological statement that the hour of his death has not yet come (cf. John 7:30: "his hour had not yet come"). Luke\'s brevity here is significant: no explanation is given, preserving the mysterious quality of the divine protection. The episode frames the entire Galilean ministry as moving toward a destined ending that cannot be rushed.</p>',
'31': '<p>Capernaum (modern Capernaum / Tell Hum on the northwest shore of the Sea of Galilee) is the base of operations for Jesus\' Galilean ministry. Archaeological excavations have uncovered a first-century synagogue site (the later fourth-century limestone synagogue stands atop basalt foundations that may be first-century), a basalt domestic structure venerated as Peter\'s house by the second century, and commercial fishing installations. The site is on the Via Maris trade route, explaining the presence of a Roman centurion (7:1-10) and a tax office (5:27). Capernaum was prosperous by Galilean village standards.</p>',
'32': '<p>"His teaching amazed them because his message had authority" (exousia) -- first-century synagogue teaching typically involved citing rabbinic authorities (as the Pharisees and scribes did: "Rabbi X said in the name of Rabbi Y..."). Jesus teaches differently: he speaks from his own authority rather than citing predecessors. This is the same quality Matthew notes in the Sermon on the Mount: "You have heard it said... but I say to you" (Matt 5:21-48). The exousia that marks his teaching is the same exousia that commands demons (v.36) and forgives sins (5:24) -- it is the authority of his person, not his credentials.</p>',
'33': '<p>The presence of a person with an "impure spirit" (pneuma daimoniou akathartou) in the synagogue itself is noteworthy -- demon possession was not confined to social margins in first-century Jewish understanding. Second Temple Judaism had a developed demonology: Asmodeus (Tobit), Mastema (Jubilees), Belial (DSS), Azazel (1 Enoch). Exorcism was practiced by Jewish exorcists (Acts 19:13-16; Josephus Ant. 8.46-49 describes Solomon-tradition exorcism). The synagogue setting makes this a public, official confrontation -- the unclean spirit is present at the reading of Torah, making the contrast with Jesus\' "holy" identity stark.</p>',
'34': '<p>"What do you want with us, Jesus of Nazareth?" -- the plural "us" in demon speech may reflect the plural nature of possession (cf. 8:30, Legion), the solidarity of the demonic realm, or an inclusive address on behalf of all unclean spirits threatened by Jesus\' presence. "The Holy One of God" (ho hagios tou theou) is a specific title: in the OT it is used of the consecrated priest (Ps 106:16, of Aaron) and of the divine warrior; in early Christian usage it becomes a messianic title (John 6:69; Acts 3:14). The demon\'s recognition of Jesus\' identity before any human confession is a Markan-Lukan motif of ironic disclosure.</p>',
'35': '<p>Jesus\' exorcism command -- "Be quiet! Come out of him!" (phim&#333;thēti kai exelthe) -- uses the same verb (phimoō = muzzle, silence) used of silencing unruly animals. The demon\'s convulsive exit (throwing the man down in the middle without harming him) distinguishes Jesus\' exorcism from typical ancient exorcism, which could be violent and prolonged. Jewish exorcism practices described by Josephus (Ant. 8.47: ring with Solomon\'s seal, incantation texts, burning roots) and the DSS Prayer of Nabonidus contrast with Jesus\' immediate, word-only exorcism -- no ritual paraphernalia, no prolonged formula.</p>',
'36': '<p>"What words these are! With authority and power he gives orders to impure spirits and they come out" -- Luke\'s crowd distinguishes two qualities: logos (word/authority) and dynamis (power). The pairing of exousia (authority/legal right) and dynamis (miraculous power) appears again in 4:14 and Luke 9:1 (when Jesus sends the Twelve with "power and authority over all demons"). In Hellenistic philosophy, a word (logos) with real power (dynamis) to effect change was the mark of a divine being. The crowd\'s astonishment is not merely at the exorcism but at the mode: command alone, instantaneous compliance.</p>',
'37': '<p>"Reports about him spread throughout the surrounding area" -- the Galilee region encompassed the cities of the Decapolis to the east, Phoenician territory to the north, Samaria to the south, and Gaulanitis (the Golan) to the northeast. The fame narrative in Luke (5:15; 7:17) contrasts with Jesus\' frequent attempts at discretion (4:41; 5:14) -- the healing ministry generates public attention he does not seek. Josephus describes Galilee as densely populated (Life 235: "208 villages and towns"), making rapid rumor-spread through the region plausible.</p>',
'38': '<p>The house of Simon (Peter) has been associated archaeologically with a first-century domestic structure at Capernaum venerated as early as the second century CE. The structure shows evidence of repeated plaster applications and graffiti that include the name "Peter" in various languages, suggesting continuous Christian veneration (later covered by a Byzantine octagonal church). That Peter is married is confirmed by 1 Cor 9:5 ("a believing wife, as do the other apostles and the Lord\'s brothers and Cephas"). First-century Galilean houses were typically single or two-room structures with a central courtyard shared by an extended family group.</p>',
'39': '<p>"He bent over her and rebuked the fever" -- Luke, as a physician (Col 4:14), uses the medical-adjacent term "high fever" (pyretos megas) -- the only NT writer to specify the intensity of fever. The rebuking of a fever as if it were a demonic entity (the same verb epitimaō used in v.35 for the demon) reflects the ancient understanding that diseases could be caused by demonic affliction (cf. 13:16: the bent woman "whom Satan has kept bound"). The immediate effect -- she got up and began to serve them -- demonstrates complete recovery, as fevers typically leave a period of weakness. Luke\'s medical eye notes the completeness of the cure.</p>',
'40': '<p>"As the sun was setting" -- the end of Sabbath (at sunset Saturday), when the Sabbath restrictions on carrying and travel lifted, the people brought those who were sick. The Sabbath technically ended when three stars were visible (m. Shabbat 2:7); until then, carrying the sick to Jesus would violate the Sabbath work prohibition. The gathering of the whole town at Simon\'s door mirrors the synagogue assembly of the morning -- Capernaum has been electrified by the day\'s events. The individual healing through laying on of hands (epititheis tas cheiras) was a recognized gesture of blessing and healing in both Jewish (Gen 48:14) and early Christian practice (Acts 6:6; 8:17).</p>',
'41': '<p>The demons\' confessional cry "You are the Son of God" (Huios tou theou) is silenced by Jesus because they "knew he was the Messiah" (Christon auton einai). This Messianic Secret motif (prominent in Mark) appears in Luke as selective suppression: demons may know Jesus\' identity, but their testimony is not the appropriate vehicle for his self-disclosure. The contrast is with human witnesses like Peter (9:20) and the centurion (23:47) whose confessions are received. In Second Temple Judaism, divine sonship was used of Israel as a whole (Exod 4:22; Hos 11:1), of the Davidic king (2 Sam 7:14; Ps 2:7), and of righteous individuals (Wis 2:18) -- the demonic recognition goes beyond any of these to identify the specific person of Jesus.</p>',
'42': '<p>Jesus\' withdrawal to a solitary place for prayer is a Lukan pattern (3:21; 5:16; 6:12; 9:18, 28; 11:1; 22:41). Luke adds prayer to several episodes where Mark/Matthew have none, reflecting his theological emphasis on Jesus\' Spirit-sustained relationship with the Father. The crowd\'s attempt to keep him from leaving (katechoō = hold back, restrain) reflects the Galilean enthusiasm that Jesus consistently resists -- his ministry is not captive to any one community\'s needs or expectations. The scene anticipates the pattern of rejection and departure that characterizes the Galilean ministry.</p>',
'43': '<p>"I must proclaim the good news of the kingdom of God" (dei me euangelisasthai) -- dei (it is necessary, I must) is one of Luke\'s characteristic divine-necessity terms, appearing at key junctures: 2:49 (I must be in my Father\'s house), 4:43 (I must preach), 9:22 (the Son of Man must suffer), 13:33 (a prophet must die in Jerusalem), 22:37 (this must be fulfilled). The dei frames Jesus\' ministry as divinely commissioned necessity rather than human preference. The scope -- "to the other towns also" -- drives the mission outward in exactly the direction Nazareth has refused (vv.23-27).</p>',
'44': '<p>Luke\'s summary of the synagogue preaching circuit in "Judea" (some manuscripts read "Galilee," which matches the geographic context; "Judea" in Luke can refer to the whole Jewish land rather than just the southern province, cf. 1:5; 6:17; 7:17; 23:5). The synagogue circuit was a natural infrastructure for itinerant teaching: each town\'s synagogue provided a venue, an audience, and a social network. The summary closes the Nazareth-Capernaum unit and opens the way for the disciple-call narrative (ch5), which will give the mission its ongoing human form.</p>',
},
'5': {
'1': '<p>The Lake of Gennesaret (= Sea of Galilee / Kinneret) is identified by this name in Josephus (War 3.463; Ant. 5.84) and 1 Macc 11:67. The fishing industry on the lake employed a significant portion of the Galilean labor force; archaeological evidence at Capernaum, Bethsaida, and Magdala includes fish-processing installations, net weights, and a first-century fishing boat (the "Jesus Boat," found in 1986). The lake is ca. 21 km long and 13 km wide at its widest, lying 213 m below sea level. Commercial fishing was organized around partnerships (koin&#333;noi, v.10) and involved significant capital investment in boats and nets.</p>',
'2': '<p>Two boats (ploiaria) were standing at the shore while the fishermen washed their nets. Net-washing after the night\'s fishing removed weeds, debris, and small fish; the nets were then dried and repaired before the next outing. Night fishing was standard on the lake (John 21:3-4) -- warmer water drove fish deeper during the day, while cooler night temperatures brought them to the surface. The return of fishermen after an unsuccessful night of work establishes the miracle\'s setting: this is not casual fishing but professional effort that has yielded nothing.</p>',
'3': '<p>Jesus uses Simon\'s boat as a floating teaching platform -- a practical solution to crowd pressure from the lake shore. The rabbis taught in synagogues, temple courts, and outdoors; teaching from a boat was unusual but not unprecedented. The crowd\'s pressing (ep&#275;konto) reflects Luke\'s consistent portrait of popular enthusiasm for Jesus\' teaching. The detail that Jesus "sat down" (kathisas) to teach confirms the seated posture of authoritative Jewish teaching (cf. 4:20; Matt 5:1; 23:2).</p>',
'4': '<p>"Put out into deep water" (ep&#257;nagag&#275; eis to bathos) -- the deep water (bathos) is the middle of the lake, away from the shallows where daytime fishing was possible. The instruction reverses normal fishing practice: go deeper in the daylight when fish are not available. Jesus addresses Simon directly and specifically, anticipating his leadership role. Simon\'s response (v.5) combines professional skepticism with personal submission -- he knows the lake conditions, but he will comply on the basis of Jesus\' word (epi de t&#333; rh&#275;mati sou).</p>',
'5': '<p>Simon\'s response "Master" (Epistat&#275;) is a Lukan title for Jesus used by disciples and petitioners (8:24, 45; 9:33, 49; 17:13) -- different from "rabbi" or "teacher" and unique to Luke among the Gospels. It carries the sense of overseer, commander, or one in charge. The acknowledgment "we worked hard all night and haven\'t caught anything" establishes both the professional exhaustion and the impossibility of further success. "But because you say so, I will let down the nets" is the pivot of faith: compliance without rational expectation.</p>',
'6': '<p>The miraculous catch (icthyon plethos poly = a great multitude of fish) was so large that the nets began to tear (dierr&#275;gnuto). The scale is deliberately excessive -- this is not a good day\'s catch but an impossible haul. The miracle echoes Ezekiel\'s vision of the restored fishing industry (Ezek 47:10: "fishermen will stand along the shore; there will be places for spreading nets"). In the post-resurrection parallel (John 21:1-14), the same miracle is repeated: 153 large fish, the nets not breaking. The Lukan episode functions as a calling narrative (the catch = the future mission harvest).</p>',
'7': '<p>The partners (metochoi, a term for business co-partners) in the other boat are signaled for help. The partnership structure (koin&#333;nia) of Galilean fishing was economically sophisticated: boats, nets, and labor were shared across family and business networks. James and John, sons of Zebedee, are named as Simon\'s partners -- establishing the network of relationships before the formal call of v.10-11. Both boats fill to sinking (h&#333;ste bythizesthai auta = so that they were beginning to sink) -- the miraculous abundance threatens to consume the very vessels it fills, a symbol of the mission\'s overwhelming scope.</p>',
'8': '<p>"Go away from me, Lord; I am a sinful man!" (Exelthe ap\' emou, hoti an&#275;r hamartolos eimi, Kyrie) -- Simon\'s response is the OT pattern of the creature encountering the holy: Isaiah\'s "Woe to me, I am ruined" at the seraphim vision (Isa 6:5), Gideon\'s "I will die for I have seen the angel of the Lord face to face" (Judg 6:22), and Ezekiel\'s prostration (Ezek 1:28). The awareness of unworthiness before holiness is not false modesty but the creaturely recognition of the chasm between human sinfulness and divine presence. Simon\'s use of Kyrios (Lord) here is Luke\'s first application of the resurrection title to the earthly Jesus in this context.</p>',
'9': '<p>The astonishment (thambos = amazement, awe) that seized Simon and all his companions was caused by the catch -- not merely wonder at a large haul but the recognition that this is a supernatural sign. Thambos in Luke appears at divine encounters (4:36; 5:9) and is the Lukan equivalent of the OT fear of God (yir\'ah) at theophanic moments. The event crosses the line between remarkable fortune and divine intervention -- the fishermen know the lake well enough to recognize that what happened was categorically impossible by natural causes.</p>',
'10': '<p>James and John, the sons of Zebedee (with their business partners), will form with Simon the inner circle of disciples (8:51; 9:28). The family enterprise of Zebedee appears in Mark 1:20 to employ hired workers, suggesting a prosperous operation. Jesus\' word to Simon -- "from now on you will catch people" (z&#333;gr&#333;n es&#275;, present participle = catching alive) -- reworks the fishing metaphor into a mission metaphor: z&#333;gre&#333; means literally "to catch alive/take alive" (used of capturing warriors alive rather than killing them, 2 Tim 2:26). The future mission will not kill but give life.</p>',
'11': '<p>"They pulled their boats up on shore, left everything, and followed him" -- the abandonment of the boats, nets, and the largest catch of their lives is the radical detachment that characterizes the disciple-call in all three Synoptics (Mark 1:18, 20; Matt 4:20, 22). Luke adds "left everything" (aphentes panta) -- the absolute renunciation formula that will appear again with Levi (5:28) and the rich ruler (18:23). In an honor-shame society, the boats and nets represented a family\'s entire capital and social identity; to leave them was to abandon economic security and social standing for an itinerant, homeless ministry.</p>',
'12': '<p>Leprosy (lepra in NT Greek) was not necessarily Hansen\'s disease but a category covering various chronic skin conditions defined by the Levitical purity code (Lev 13-14). The social consequences were severe: the leper was declared "unclean" by the priest, required to live outside the community, tear their clothes, keep their hair disheveled, cover their mouth, and call "Unclean! Unclean!" when others approached (Lev 13:45-46). Social isolation combined with economic inability meant lepers depended entirely on charity. The man in Luke is "covered with leprosy" (pl&#275;r&#275;s lepras = full of leprosy), indicating advanced disease affecting much of his body.</p>',
'13': '<p>Jesus "reached out his hand and touched the man" -- the touch is the most provocative element. By touching a leper, Jesus contracted ritual uncleanness (Lev 5:3). That Jesus touches first and commands "be clean" (katharisth&#275;ti) simultaneously illustrates the reversal at the heart of his ministry: rather than uncleanness transferring from the leper to the clean Jesus, Jesus\' purity overcomes the uncleanness. The cleansing was immediate (euthe&#333;s = at once). The parallel in 2 Kgs 5:11 (Naaman expected Elisha to wave his hand over the leprosy) highlights the personal, physical intimacy of Jesus\' healing over Elisha\'s distance-healing.</p>',
'14': '<p>"Don\'t tell anyone" -- the privacy instruction is paradoxical given the public nature of the healing. The instruction to "show yourself to the priest" follows Lev 14:2-32 exactly: the cleansed person must present themselves to the priest, who examines the skin and performs the specified purification ritual over eight days with two birds, cedar wood, scarlet yarn, and hyssop. This is expensive and time-consuming -- Jesus insists on full Torah compliance, not a shortcut. "As a testimony to them" (eis martyrion autois) means testimony to the priests of Jesus\' Torah faithfulness, and to the community that the man is genuinely restored to full social and religious participation.</p>',
'15': '<p>The withdrawal pattern appears here as a response to growing fame. "News about him spread all the more" (diercheto de mallon ho logos) is Lukan irony: the instruction to silence increases the report. Crowds gathered from all directions to hear Jesus and to be healed -- Luke uses "wilderness" (er&#275;mous topous = desolate places) as the retreat location, linking the prayer-withdrawal to the post-baptism wilderness (4:1) and anticipating Gethsemane (22:39-44). The crowds that pursue Jesus into the wilderness also echo the manna-wilderness: the one who refuses to turn stones into bread nonetheless will feed a multitude (9:10-17).</p>',
'16': '<p>"Jesus often withdrew to lonely places and prayed" -- Luke\'s prayer summary verses punctuate the narrative at moments of transition or mounting pressure: before the baptism (3:21), after the leper healing (5:16), before choosing the Twelve (6:12), before Peter\'s confession (9:18), at the Transfiguration (9:28), teaching the Lord\'s Prayer (11:1), and Gethsemane (22:41). The pattern of withdrawing from demanding ministry to re-engage the Father reflects Luke\'s portrayal of Jesus as the model for Christian prayer -- the community\'s prayer practice (Acts 1:14; 2:42; 4:24-31) mirrors Jesus\' own habit.</p>',
'17': '<p>The formal opposition makes its first appearance: Pharisees and teachers of the law (nomodidaskaloi = law-teachers, a Lukan word also at Acts 5:34 and 1 Tim 1:7) came from every village of Galilee, Judea, and Jerusalem. The geographical scope signals a coordinated response -- this is not local curiosity but a deputation. The Pharisees were a reform movement within Judaism (ca. 150 BCE - 70 CE) focused on precise Torah observance and the development of the Oral Torah. The scribes/teachers of the law (grammateis / nomodidaskaloi) were professional Torah interpreters who made legal rulings. Together they represent the official interpretive establishment. "The power of the Lord was with him to heal" (v.17b) is Luke\'s narrative signal that what follows will demonstrate divine authority challenging their authority.</p>',
'18': '<p>Palestinian domestic architecture in the first century used flat clay roofs supported by wooden beams. Luke uses keram&#333;n (tiles) -- either describing a Greek-style tiled roof or adapting Mark\'s description for his Hellenistic audience (Mark 2:4 specifies "they dug through the roof"). The effort of four men carrying a pallet (klinidion = small bed/mat) up exterior stairs and through the roof to lower it into a crowded room demonstrates extraordinary determination -- a determination Jesus interprets as "faith" (v.20). The paralytic (paralelymenos = loosened/broken in limb) was unable to act on his own; his friends\' faith mediates for him.</p>',
'19': '<p>The courtyard scenario in a typical Galilean house: the crowd fills both the room where Jesus teaches and the doorway, making entry impossible. The friends carry the paralytic up to the flat roof (exterior stairs were common), remove part of the roof, and lower him on his mat into the open space in front of Jesus. Luke\'s keram&#333;n may reflect that he describes this for readers who know tiled Mediterranean roofs better than clay Palestinian roofs. The lowering through the roof and into the middle (eis to meson) of the crowd before Jesus is a bold act that cannot be ignored.</p>',
'20': '<p>"Friend, your sins are forgiven" (Anthr&#333;pe, apheontai soi hai hamartiai sou) -- Jesus addresses the man directly and personally (anthr&#333;pe is a term of familiar address). The pronouncement of forgiveness before the healing makes the healing secondary -- it is the spiritual state, not the physical, that Jesus addresses first. Aphesis (forgiveness/release) is a Jubilee word (Lev 25:10 LXX; Isa 61:1) -- the same lexical field as "release to the captives" in 4:18. The connection between sin and physical suffering was a common assumption in Second Temple Judaism (John 9:2: "who sinned, this man or his parents?"), though Jesus will challenge it (13:2-5).</p>',
'21': '<p>"Who can forgive sins but God alone?" (tis dynatai aphienai hamartias ei m&#275; monos ho theos?) -- the theological objection is correct within the framework of Second Temple Jewish monotheism. Only God can forgive sins against God -- and all sins are ultimately against God (Ps 51:4: "Against you, you only, have I sinned"). The scribes and Pharisees are not theologically confused; their objection accurately represents the Jewish understanding of divine prerogative. What they are unprepared for is the possibility that the one who stands before them has divine authority. The charge of blasphemy was a capital offence (Lev 24:16; m. Sanhedrin 7:5) -- a charge that will return at the trial (22:66-71).</p>',
'22': '<p>Jesus\' knowledge of the scribes\' inner dialogue (dialogismoi = calculations/reasonings) is presented as a claim to divine insight. In Jewish thought, God alone knows the heart (1 Sam 16:7; 1 Kgs 8:39; Ps 139:1-4; Jer 17:10). The question "Which is easier -- to say \'Your sins are forgiven\' or to say \'Get up and walk\'?" is a rhetorical trap: both are impossible without divine authority, but the first is unverifiable while the second is immediately testable. Jesus will use the testable miracle to authenticate the untestable forgiveness -- the physical healing as sign of the spiritual reality.</p>',
'23': '<p>"That you may know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins" -- the Son of Man (ho Huios tou anthr&#333;pou) title is used here for the first time in Luke (subsequent uses: 6:5, 22; 7:34; 9:22, 26, 44, 58; 11:30; 12:8, 10, 40; 17:22-30; 18:8, 31; 19:10; 21:27, 36; 22:22, 48, 69; 24:7). The title derives from Dan 7:13-14 (one "like a son of man" receives authority from the Ancient of Days) and was used in Jewish apocalyptic for a heavenly figure (1 Enoch 46-48; 4 Ezra 13). Jesus applies it to himself in an earthly, present context -- the exousia delegated to the heavenly Son of Man is exercised on earth.</p>',
'24': '<p>"Get up, take your mat and go home" -- the three-fold command demonstrates complete restoration: the paralytic stands (anistathai = rise), takes the mat that was his disability marker, and walks home. The reversal is complete: the man who was carried in on a mat now carries the mat out under his own power. In the context of v.17 (the Pharisees observing with critical intent), the physical miracle serves as the divine authentication of the forgiveness claim -- it answers the unverifiable with the undeniable. The public setting ensures this cannot be dismissed as private suggestibility.</p>',
'25': '<p>The formerly paralyzed man goes home "praising God" (doxazon ton theon) -- the standard Lukan response to miraculous events (5:26; 7:16; 13:13; 17:15; 18:43; 23:47). The community response (v.26) adds "filled with awe and praised God" -- the Greek ekplexis (overwhelm/stun) and the doxological response together constitute the appropriate human reaction to the in-breaking of divine power in the healing/forgiveness complex.</p>',
'26': '<p>"We have seen remarkable things today" (eidamen paradoxa s&#275;meron) -- the crowd\'s response uses paradoxa, a word Luke uses only here in the NT, meaning things that violate normal expectation, marvels. The community is overwhelmed (ekplexis = struck out of normal consciousness) and their praise goes to God (edoxazon ton theon). The Pharisees\' silent theological objection (v.21) is swamped by the crowd\'s vocal praise -- the people have drawn the correct inference from the miracle even if the authorities have not.</p>',
'27': '<p>Levi the tax collector was sitting at his tax booth (telōnion) -- the customs post, likely at Capernaum on the Via Maris trade route or at the border between Herod Antipas\'s Galilee and Philip\'s territory. Tax collectors (telōnai) in the first century were local contractors who purchased the right to collect tolls and customs from the Roman or Herodian administration, keeping any excess above the contracted amount as profit. The system incentivized extortion and made the telōnai socially despised -- associated with Gentile collaboration, financial dishonesty, and ritual impurity from handling Gentile money. Levi is also called Matthew (Mark 2:14 is also "Levi son of Alphaeus"; some identify him with Matthew the apostle).</p>',
'28': '<p>"Leaving everything" (katalipōn panta) -- the same phrase used of the fishermen (aphentes panta, 5:11). The tax collector\'s abandonment is even more dramatic: the fishermen left boats and nets, which they could in principle return to (cf. John 21:3). Levi leaves the telōnion, the source of income, the contracted right, the established livelihood -- to follow an itinerant teacher with no fixed abode. The parallel structure of the disciple-calls (fishermen + tax collector) signals that the community around Jesus will include socially diverse members -- manual laborers and financial collaborators alike.</p>',
'29': '<p>Levi\'s great banquet (doch&#275;n megal&#275;n) for Jesus at his house drew "a large crowd of tax collectors and others" -- the social network of a tax collector would naturally include other telōnai, merchants, and those on the social margins of respectable Jewish society. Table fellowship (commensality) was the primary mechanism of social boundary maintenance in Mediterranean culture: you ate with your social equals, your family, and those you included in your community. Jesus\' recumbence at table with tax collectors and "sinners" (hamartolos = those who either lived immorally or practiced occupations considered incompatible with Torah) is a deliberate, visible boundary-crossing.</p>',
'30': '<p>"The Pharisees and the teachers of the law who belonged to their sect complained to his disciples" (egongyzon) -- egongyzō is the LXX verb for Israel\'s grumbling in the wilderness (Exod 15:24; 16:7-8; 17:3; Num 11:1; 14:2; cf. 1 Cor 10:10). Luke uses this specific word at 5:30, 15:2, and 19:7 in connection with table-fellowship controversies involving tax collectors and sinners -- deliberately evoking the wilderness murmuring tradition. The community around Jesus is the new exodus people, and the opposition\'s complaint is the same old wilderness rebellion against God\'s provision.</p>',
'31': '<p>"It is not the healthy who need a doctor, but the sick" -- the physician metaphor is fitting both for Luke (Col 4:14) and for the social context: the comparison of the teacher/healer to a physician is attested in Hellenistic moral philosophy (Plutarch uses it of Socrates; Epictetus compares his school to a physician\'s surgery). The metaphor reframes the table-fellowship controversy: the "sinners" are the sick patients, not the healthy excluded. The physician\'s presence among the sick is not contamination but treatment.</p>',
'32': '<p>"I have not come to call the righteous, but sinners to repentance" (eis metanoian) -- metanoia (repentance, turning) is a Lukan keyword: 3:3 (John\'s baptism of repentance), 3:8 (fruit worthy of repentance), 5:32, 10:13, 11:32, 13:3, 5; 15:7, 10; 16:30; 17:3-4; 24:47. Repentance in Luke is not merely sorrow for sin but a comprehensive re-orientation of life -- the prodigal son "coming to himself" and returning to the father (15:17-20). The call of Levi and the subsequent banquet is simultaneously a call to repentance and its immediate expression in table fellowship.</p>',
'33': '<p>The question about fasting contrasts John\'s disciples and the Pharisees\' disciples with Jesus\' disciples. Jewish fasting practices in the Second Temple period: the Pharisees fasted twice a week (Monday and Thursday, Didache 8:1 criticizes "hypocrites" for this); the Day of Atonement was the only biblically mandated fast (Lev 16:29-34); voluntary fasting was practiced for mourning (2 Sam 12:16), repentance (Jonah 3:5; 1 Kgs 21:27), and prophetic preparation (Dan 10:3). The observation that Jesus\' disciples neither fast nor pray like others suggests the disciples\' relative informality about structured pious practice.</p>',
'34': '<p>"Can you make the friends of the bridegroom fast while he is with them?" -- the wedding metaphor is eschatological: the kingdom of God is consistently compared to a wedding banquet in the Synoptics (Matt 22:2-14; 25:1-13; Luke 14:16-24). The bridegroom\'s presence is the condition of celebration, not mourning -- and Jesus is the bridegroom. The metaphor implicitly identifies Jesus with the divine bridegroom of the OT (God as husband of Israel: Isa 54:5; 62:5; Jer 31:32; Ezek 16; Hos 2:19-20). Fasting is the practice of absence and longing; feasting is the practice of presence and joy.</p>',
'35': '<p>"The time will come when the bridegroom will be taken from them; in those days they will fast" -- the first explicit Lukan passion prediction, veiled in the wedding metaphor. "Taken from them" (aparthē) echoes Isa 53:8 LXX: "his life was taken away from the earth." The future fasting of the disciples points to the period after the crucifixion-ascension and before the parousia -- the Church\'s present age. The early church did fast (Acts 13:2-3; 14:23; Didache 8), and this verse provides the theological rationale.</p>',
'36': '<p>The parable of the new patch on an old garment inverts normal clothing repair logic: no one cuts new cloth to patch old -- the new piece would shrink, tear the old, and the patch would not match anyway. The incompatibility of new and old in this application: Jesus\' teaching cannot be simply appended to the old religious framework. It requires new fabric -- a new structure, not a patch on the old. The point is not that the old (Torah, covenant, tradition) is worthless but that the new wine of the kingdom cannot be contained within the forms developed for a different age.</p>',
'37': '<p>"And no one pours new wine into old wineskins" -- new wine continues to ferment and expand; the already-stretched old skins (dried leather bottles) cannot absorb the pressure and will burst. The new skins have enough elasticity to accommodate the expanding wine. The parable extends the previous image: the kingdom\'s dynamic reality requires new forms adequate to its character. Luke\'s context in the fasting controversy: the old forms of Pharisaic piety (regular fasting, ritual prayer) are the old wineskins; the new reality of Jesus\' presence demands forms that can accommodate it.</p>',
'38': '<p>"New wine must be poured into new wineskins" -- the positive conclusion of the previous negative examples. The new wine is the dynamic reality of the kingdom; the new wineskins are the forms adequate to it -- table fellowship with sinners, joyful celebration in the bridegroom\'s presence, the freedom of the physician among the sick. The imagery was familiar to any Mediterranean audience: leather wine containers (askos = wineskin) were a common household item, and the behavior of new wine in old containers was a practical reality.</p>',
'39': '<p>"And no one after drinking old wine wants the new, for they say, \'The old is better.\'" -- this final saying, unique to Luke, adds a psychologically realistic coda: people resist the new not because it is inferior but because they are accustomed to the old. The conservative preference for the familiar is a natural human pattern. In the context of the controversy, this explains the Pharisees\' resistance: they have been shaped by the old forms and find them satisfying. The saying is not a condemnation but an observation -- a gentle acknowledgment that the transition to the new is genuinely difficult and that human preference does not determine what is actually better.</p>',
}
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'luke')
    merge_comm(existing, NEW)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'luke', existing)
    import json as _json, pathlib as _pl
    inter = _json.loads((_pl.Path(__file__).parent.parent / 'data/interlinear/luke.json').read_text())
    for ch in [4, 5]:
        ck = str(ch)
        have = set(existing.get(ck, {}).keys())
        need = set(inter.get(ck, {}).keys())
        missing = sorted(int(v) for v in (need - have))
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(have)}/{len(need)} -- missing: {missing}')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
